The apostrophe is generally not used to mark plurals in Quikscript or
Shavian because they&#39;re phonetically and phonemically identical to
possessives. But for contractions, where words are shortened and
connected, they&#39;re usually retained.&lt;br&gt;
As for that accent, I don&#39;t have a copy of the Quikscript manual on
hand--I know I saved it somewhere--but isn&#39;t it just a short vertical
line or dot? If so, then there is a combining character for it in
Unicode. The character &quot;COMBINING VERTICAL LINE ABOVE&quot; at the codepoint
030D, and the &quot;COMBINING DOT ABOVE&quot; is 0307. Neither is specific to any
script, so it should be fine to use them with Quikscript. Here are both
of them on the letter &lt;i&gt;o&lt;/i&gt; for reference: o&#781; o&#775;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Those may not display correctly. Using Thunderbird on my Mac, only the
first one does. Assuming you&#39;ve got decent Unicode support, it&#39;s
functionality will depend mostly on the font you&#39;re using. So as long
as your Quikscript font has the character in a working state, it should
display correctly.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
However, I don&#39;t think setting Senior Quikscript on a computer will be
that difficult. It&#39;s pretty easy with Opentype, among others, to
automate selection of alternates and ligatures. It would be more work
for the designer (I&#39;ve considered taking on the task myself), but none
at all for the user. In the Latin alphabet, for example, it&#39;s customary
to replace certain groups of letters with ligatures to make them fit
more neatly together. Lowercase &quot;fi&quot; and &quot;fl&quot; will be replaced
automatically, if the software supports it, with the ligatures &quot;&#64257;&quot; and
&quot;&#64258;&quot;. Some fonts provide even more including &quot;ff&quot;, &quot;fj&quot;, &quot;fk&quot; etc., as
well as many with a long s instead of f. This kind of replacement is
used extensively in Arabic because of its cursive nature and works
perfectly without any user input. You just have to know what sequences
of letters require what contextual replacements. That&#39;s where it seems
to get a bit complicated when you have to account for pairs and
triplets and so on such that &quot;&lt;font face=&quot;king plus&quot;&gt;anl&lt;/font&gt;&quot; gets
replaced with &quot;&lt;font face=&quot;king plus&quot;&gt;uGl&lt;/font&gt;&quot;, but not after
another letter that connects on top. But that&#39;s as complicated as it
gets. And it&#39;s not as bad as it sounds: some of this can be simplified
by grouping characters into classes according to how they connect on
each side. Then replacements can be done automatically for each class
so that everything runs together. If we give them plain-English names
(I don&#39;t know about other systems, but OpenType generally assigns them
numbers), we could call them &quot;top-top&quot;, &quot;top-bottom&quot;, &quot;bottom-top&quot;, and
&quot;bottom-bottom&quot;. Then write replacements to make sure tops and bottoms
go together.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
Now, getting software to support these features is another matter. It&#39;s
just not quite there yet.&lt;br&gt;
